title: For Sale:  WWI GI 1911 Parts
postcontent:
Please read entire listing.

I have decided to let go of my 1911 parts, which are a collection that was amassed over decades of collecting. These are rare parts, and if you have a WWI 1911 that has incorrect parts on it, the value is hurt significantly.

So, the investment of a couple hundred dollars to make yours correct, could increase the value by 4x or 5x that amount, or more. When knowing collectors look at a 1911, they scrutinize every part, and expect it to be right.

Here is all I have, and the prices (the number corresponds with the tag in the photo - due to Armslist size restrictions, there is a Photobucket link below to copy / paste in your browser):

18: Two-tone "R" stamped (Risdon Mfg Co.) magazine = $125
19: Two-tone "R" stamped (Risdon Mfg Co.) magazine = $100
20: Two-tone "R" stamped (Risdon Mfg Co.) magazine = $100
56: Wooden 'Double Diamond' grips (pair) = $275
54: Wooden 28-row Checkered grips (pair) = $300
55: Wooden 'Double Diamond' grips (pair) = $300
57: Wooden 28-row Checkered grip (single / rt panel only) = $50
10: Vertical "H P" barrel = $300
9: Intertwined "H P" barrel = $300
31: Long Trigger = $100
32: Long Trigger = $125
44: Checkered slide stop = $110
45: Checkered slide stop = $110
46: Checkered slide stop = $110
36: Flat mainspring housing = $100
48: Long wide-spur hammer with bordered checkering = $110
49: Long wide-spur hammer with no border on checkering = $110
50: Long wide-spur hammer checkered to edge, no border = $110
27: Short-tang grip safety = $70
1: Slide, has early U-notch rear sight, narrow front sight, and "M1911 A1 US ARMY" on right side - complete with firing pin, extractor, and firing-pin stop = $400

If you are serious about buying, please e-mail me what you are interested in.

I will only take a USPS or Western Union money order.

As it relates to my prices, I have put them below what eBay auctions are closing at for like parts, and what I'm seeing at shows.

I beg you, please do not send me an e-mail complaining about where I've set my prices. I am not forcing anyone to buy them, and if you are a serious collector, you know what they're worth. Look at what correct WWI barrels are selling for on eBay ($400+). Grips are astronomical in price, but again, if you have an otherwise correct WWI USGI 1911, and it has after-market grips on it, it really hurts value.

If you buy multiple parts, I may work with you on price a LITTLE, but I am not going to give them away. These are getting harder and harder to find, and are only going up in price. We're coming up on the 100th anniversary of WWI, which is going to cause a spike in prices as well.

I will consider trades, but nothing modern. Would need to be militaria (helmets, firearms, inert ordnance, etc) from WWI or WWII, any country.

All photos here: s1173.beta.photobucket.com/user/gi1911/library/WWI%20Parts (you will have to manually type the "http://" in front of it)

Thank you.

title: For Sale:  Bersa Thunder 9 Pro (Includes Ammo!)
postcontent:
Bersa Thunder 9 Pro
- I'll throw in one 50 round box of ammo for full price offer
- Picatinny rail under barrel (a must have for home protection - great for mounting a light)
- DA/SA trigger with manual safety/decocker
- 3 high capactiy magazines (2-15 round and 1-17 round) 
- Minor wear where expected (slide, slide rail, metal to metal contact points, etc.) and some very minor holster wear on slide
- Comes in plastic case (original cardboard box also comes with it)

This pistol shoots great.  I bought this as a project (got a good deal because it came with no mags).  I had some leftover factory Beretta 92/M9 mags and had recently read about guys modifying these to work in the Bersa.  All they need is a repositioned mag catch slot (the wider slot that you can see in the photo).  Just to let you know how I did this:
1. Remove internals from mag - reinstall base plate only
2. Remove rubber grip from gun
3. Remove mag release from gun
4. Seat mag (with base plate) in mag well
All the above allows the mag catch slot to be lined up in exactly the correct location (no need to take measurements, use calipers, etc.)
5. Drill pilot hole
6. Expand pilot hole to allow hand files to be inserted
7. Hand file to obtain correct length and width of slot (inserting into magwell throughout the process to ensure alignment is still correct)
- We're talking about some hard steel when it comes to these magazines, so this was a fairly time consuming process (however, it's worth it because Beretta mags can be found much cheaper than Bersa). 

Shot this recently to test function of the mags.  They all seat with a satisfying click.  The base is nice and flush with the bottom of grip.  Shot slow, shot fast and absolutely no failures.  The slide hold open feature even works just like original Bersa mags.

You will not be disappointed with the functionality.  I would keep it, but I already have a Glock 19 that serves the same purpose (similar size/capacity) and wifey says one has to go.  

MUST have CPL and driver's license and be willing to complete bill of sale.

Price is firm.
The prices are largely based on what I've seen these going for on Gun Broker.
- Keep in mind, no tax/shipping/FFL fees with FTF transfers!

Prefer meeting near Port Orchard.
Depending on schedule I'm will to travel within Gig Harbor/Silverdale/Belfair area.

Note: I don't have access to my personal e-mail during the day - I'll answer all e-mails in the evening after I get home.

title: For Sale:  COLOR-CASE TTN-Cimarron 1878 . -- SXS 12ga 20 COACHGUN
postcontent: his gun was featured in the “GUNS of the OLD WEST” Magazine 09 summer addition. Not long after that article came out the TTN SXS's weren't available. They are now available again but it is my understanding this will be the last batch imported by Cimoarron. The TTN is the way to go if you want a true hammer gun. It is the ruler of the SASS Classic Cowboy catagory shotguns......................................... TNN has addressed several issues with this gun. Most of the other CAS SXS’s don’t have enough drop in the stock for CAS ground targets. They tend to shoot high for most people. The TTN has plenty drop for shooting at ground targets very similar to the originals. It is a heavy built 3"chambered long forcing cone gun so felt recoil in minimal with this guns.The hammers are close together making it easy to cock both with one thumb. For these color-case guns I receive these guns as all blue, I take them apart de-burred and de-horn the hammers and send the parts out for true bone meal and charcoal color-case hardening.....................The flat matte finish on the wood gets several coats of hand rubbed Tru-Oil. Then the parts are refitted and polished so the gun will work with the lighter springs. Then, the hammer springs,and the firing pin springs reduced and installed.....................The triggers are switched suides for righthamded shooters (3rd picture down on a different gun). The "V" type top latch spring and the sear springs are fitted with the more reilable piano wire springs. When finished the gun easily cocks both hammers at the same time with one thumb. The latch lever will open easier and the barrels will fall open wide of their own weight. For the barrels, the chambers are polish and chamfered for easy loading and unloading

title: For Sale:  Spyderco Street Beat Knife Fixed Blade
postcontent:
Fred Perrin is a Parisian custom knifemaker, a former French Army Commando and a world ranked martial artist. His Street Beat fixed-blade knife reflects all three influences. Handle and blade are roughly equal weight. Where they join is a deep finger choil doubling as a hand guard. This spot marks the location of a balance point, sometimes referred to as a sweet-spot, making the knife noticeably responsive in the hand.
The Street Beat is constructed from a full-length piece of steel set between Micarta handle scales. The scales are double pinned, expanding three-dimensionally on both ends offering the hand exceptional grip. The VG-10 clip point blade is double flat-ground with crosshatching called jimping on its spine that creates texture therefore tactile resistance against the skin of the hand and keeping the knife firmly in grip. There are two lanyard holes, a traditionally positioned handle lanyard and a small lanyard hole through the blade. Looping a thong or cord through the blade lanyard keeps your hand positioned forward on the handle even when swinging or chopping. The Street Beat comes in a black Boltaron sheath with a G-Clip fastening system

Specifications:
Overall Length: 7.19"
Blade Length: 3.5"
Cutting Edge: 3.25"
Blade Thickness: 5/32" (4mm) 
Blade Steel: VG-10

title: For Sale:  CRKT Nirk Tighe 2 Folding Knife
postcontent:
It all began last year when Canadian knifemaker Brian Tighe saw Glenn Klecker's design for his NIRK folder, a strikingly minimal design stamped and folded out of two pieces of stainless steel. Brian called Glenn, and raised the possibility of using the same lockback release mechanism with CNC-machined open-build construction. Brian went to work and produced his custom NIRK Tighe from exotic materials,which immediately won the Most Innovative Custom Design Award at the 2010 Blade Show. 
All that was left for us to do was to convert his custom into a faithful production model. Our version of the NIRK Tighe features 420J2 stainless steel frames which are stamped, then machined and coated with blue titanium nitride. Finally, the frame exterior is satin polished, leaving the blue interior coating, a stunning effect. 
Like the original NIRK, the knife is a lockback folder in which the spring, release bar and lock detent are all integral with the frame structure. Two pronounced finger notches provide a secure grip. Brian's blade is a graceful but strong drop point design with subtle recurve, and weight-saving reliefs cut into the spine for balance. The blade can be opened with one hand, by using a thumb on the reliefs, or by pressing the blade flipper. The blade is precision cut from premium AUS 8 stainless steel. At the blade pivot, a special caged mini ball bearing system gives fast and smooth opening action. The tighter the grip on the handle, the tighter the lockup, making this an exceptionally safe design. A custom removable stainless steel clothing/gear clip is provided. 
Glenn's original quest was to create a folder of "irreducible complexity." Brian has added a few additional parts, true, but he's also added a vast amount of design interest in what is still a very functional folder. 

Specifications:
Overall Length: 7.375" (187 mm)
Blade Length: 3.25" (82.6 mm)
Blade Thickness: 0.11" (2.8 mm)
Blade Steel: AUS 8, 58-59 HRC
Closed Length: 4.25" (108 mm)
Weight: 3.3 oz. (94 g)

To close the bolt with the manual bolt hold-open engaged, the charging handle must be pulled out, away from the gun, before the bolt will go forward. Since 1985, the Model 60 has also included a patented automatic "last-shot" bolt hold-open. This latter feature is a safety feature that locks the bolt half-way open after the last cartridge is fired, thereby allowing the safe inspection of the now-open action. This also notifies the user when the gun is empty..............During the late-1980s, the capacity of the rifle was reduced to a 15 round maximum limit, to meet New Jersey's firearms law for semi-automatic assault weapons.
